<DOC><DOCNO> AP880519-0280 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0850EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-AmfacBuyout     05-19 0250</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Amfac Buyout,0261</SECOND><HEAD>Amfac Management Proposes Buyout</HEAD><DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Amfac Inc. management, led by the president ofthe San Francisco-based conglomorate, has proposed an all-cashbuyout for the purchase of the company at a value of $41 per share.   ``The company stated that it has been advised that managementhas been discussing financing for the buyout with a leadingfinancial institution and is confident that such financing can beobtained,'' the company said in a statement issued on Wednesday ata special board of directors' meeting.   However, the statement added that ``there is as yet no firmcommitment.''   The buyout would be led by Amfac President and Chief ExecutiveOfficer Richard L. Griffith, 57.   The proposed buyout is ``strongly supported by operatingmanagement,'' said Griffith.   He said it ``strengthens our ability to develop Amfac's Hawaiiasset base in a paced and profitable manner in concert with thestate's economic needs and long-term growth goals.''   The plan is ``subject to obtaining the financing as well as anumber of other conditions,'' including approval of the board, thecompany statement said.   Meantime, the board decided not to proceed with the sale of theFred Harvey Resort operations and a 50 percent joint ventureinterest in its Hawaii land and agricultural operations. Thecompany had received an offer of $166 million for Fred Harvey.   Amfac is a diversified services company with main lines ofbusiness in food processing, hotels and resorts, retail,agriculture and property.   Revenues in 1987 were $2.2 billion.</TEXT></DOC>